1) Rename columns rename() Change column names
2) Select rows by column values filter() Remove NA samples
3) Collapse many values to a single summary summarise() Get mean from Loin weights and WHC
4) Create new variables in function to existing ones mutate() Add column with animal weight in grams
5) Pick variables by their names select() Select only factors, weight (g) & loin weights
6) Reorder rows arrange() Sort samples by weight

A short parenthesis!! - PIPING

The dplyr pipe %>% is an operator inherited from magrittr which takes the output from one function and uses it as input for the next one (just like Unix | pipe).

mean(phenot$WHC, na.rm = T)
## [1] 23.70342
phenot$WHC %>% mean(na.rm = T)
## [1] 23.70342

1) Rename columns

We use dplyr::rename() function to change specified column names.

phenot %>% 
  rename(Weight_kg = Weight..kg., Month = Weight.month, LoinW_1 = Loin.weight.1, LoinW_2 = Loin.weight.2) %>% 
  head
##   ID_sample Breed Diet Weight_kg Month LoinW_1 LoinW_2    WHC
## 1  Sample 1    IB    1      98.5    10      NA      NA     NA
## 2  Sample 1    IB    1     120.1    13    2.19    2.40 21.504
## 3  Sample 2    DU    1      99.9    10      NA      NA     NA
## 4  Sample 2    DU    1     135.4    13    2.28    2.24 23.734
## 5  Sample 3    IB    1     100.4    10      NA      NA     NA
## 6  Sample 3    IB    1     133.2    13    2.29    2.36 20.632

But this is MADNESS when we must rename 100 columns What should we do??

  1. If every column name to change follows a pattern:
    I.e., columns with .weight. in their name.
phenot %>% rename_at(vars(contains(".weight.")), funs(str_replace(., ".weight.", "W_"))) %>% head
##   ID_sample Breed Diet Weight..kg. Weight.month LoinW_1 LoinW_2    WHC
## 1  Sample 1    IB    1        98.5           10      NA      NA     NA

## 5  Sample 3    IB    1       100.4           10      NA      NA     NA
## 6  Sample 3    IB    1       133.2           13    2.29    2.36 20.632


  1. If no pattern is detected:
phenot2 <- phenot
old.cols <- which(colnames(phenot2) %in% c("Weight..kg.", "Weight.month", "Loin.weight.1", "Loin.weight.2"))
old.cols <- 4:7

colnames(phenot2)[old.cols] <- c("Weight_kg", "Month", "LoinW_1", "LoinW_2")

SOME TRAINING
Use dplyr::rename() or another method to change the column names, and save it inside phenot variable.

phenot <- phenot %>% 
  rename(Weight_kg = Weight..kg., Month = Weight.month, LoinW_1 = Loin.weight.1, LoinW_2 = Loin.weight.2)


2) Collapse many values to a single summary

At certain situations we will need to group our dataset based on one or multiple categorical columns. The summarise() function, together with group_by(), does the job.

phenot %>% 
  group_by(Breed, Diet) %>% 
  summarise_at(c("LoinW_1", "LoinW_2", "WHC"), mean, na.rm = T)
## # A tibble: 4 x 5
## # Groups:   Breed [2]
##   Breed  Diet LoinW_1 LoinW_2   WHC
##   <fct> <int>   <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 DU        1    2.25    2.20  24.4
## 2 DU        2    2.14    2.15  26.1
## 3 IB        1    2.25    2.39  22.2
## 4 IB        2    1.93    1.99  22.1


Utilities:

  • Get basic statistics for any variable(s) keeping a tabular format.
phenot %>% 
  group_by(Breed, Diet) %>% 
  summarise_at(c("LoinW_1", "LoinW_2", "WHC"), list(Mean=mean, SD=sd, Max=max, Min=min), na.rm=T)

3) Create new variables in function to existing ones

Function mutate() creates new columns based on the values of other existing columns. Now, we will create a new column which is a modification of WHC (water holding capacity), transforming the precentage units into decimals.

phenot <- phenot %>% mutate(WHC_dec = WHC/100)
as_tibble(phenot)

4) Pick variables by their names

Now, we will take only the classification factors, animal weight, loin weights and water holding capacity in decimal terms, using select()function. Notice that column order changes according to input order.

phenot_sub <- phenot %>% select(ID_sample, Breed, Diet, Weight_kg, LoinW_1, LoinW_2, WHC_dec)

5) Select rows by column values

Here we use dplyr::filter() function to subset data frame under one specific condition. For example, we would like to remove rows with NA data in our data subset.

phenot_sub <- phenot_sub %>% filter(!is.na(LoinW_1) & !is.na(LoinW_2) & !is.na(WHC_dec))

Another dplyr application is reordering rows based on the tables variables. For example, we would like to rearrange our animal samples first by breed and then by their weight.

Split cells

Our first column contains multiple gene information. We would like to split these infos into multiple columns. tidyr::separate() is perfect for the work.

fpkm_sep <- fpkm %>% 
  separate(col = "Gene.ID.Shortname.Locus", into = c("Gene_ID", "Short_name", "Locus"), sep = ";")
fpkm_sep[1:6,1:6]
##       Gene_ID Short_name             Locus      Sam1       Sam2      Sam3
## 1 XLOC_000013      DACT2 1:1414133-1424009  7.242140   7.085090  7.493450
## 2 XLOC_000014      FRMD1 1:1495817-1521666 53.336800 104.983000 75.677900
## 3 XLOC_000015     UNC93A 1:1919993-1958328  0.725882   0.550716  1.033260

unite(fpkm_sep, Gene_ID, Short_name, Locus, col = "Gene.ID.Shortname.Locus", sep = ";", remove = TRUE)

Another interesting utility is tidyr::separate_rows(), which splits one row information into multiple rows:

separate_rows(fpkm, Gene.ID.Shortname.Locus, sep=";")
##   Gene.ID.Shortname.Locus     Sam1      Sam2     Sam3     Sam4     Sam5
## 1             XLOC_000013  7.24214   7.08509  7.49345  6.03476  9.13230

Handle missing values

Lets go back to our phenot data. We already prepared them for analysis removing 10 month NA measures. But we have another option to deal with NA values using tidyr:

  • drop_na() does the same as dplyr::filter() when used for NA filtering.
  • fill() replaces NA by values present in the rows below or up.
  • replace_na() replaces NA values by a specified one. We can select different replacements for each column.

Omics data usually contain classification columns (taxonomy, functionality, gene IDs, metabolites) which can only be managed with string manipulation functions. stringr package is perfect for this.

Detect string matches

The main stringr function for locating string patterns is str_detect.

str_detect(microb$Kingdom, "Bacteria")
  • str_detect(string, pattern) == grepl(pattern, string)
  • str_which(string, pattern) == which(grepl(pattern, string))

So, why use stringr? -> 5x faster and easier syntax to be piped.

Note that these functions work on ATOMIC VECTORS, not on data frames. But some R coding can be done for this purpose.

microb %>% filter(str_detect(Kingdom, "Bacteria"))
microb %>% slice(str_which(Kingdom, "Bacteria"))

Mutate and subset strings

Tools for manipulating strings are based on str_subset and str_replace.

  • str_subset(string, pattern) == string[which(string %in% pattern)]
  • str_replace_all(string, pattern, replacement) == gsub(pattern, replacement, string)

As it happened with string matching, string replacements are faster and more intelligible with stringr code. As an example, lets compare the code below:

microb %>% select_if(is.character) %>% map_dfc(str_replace_all, "aceae", "STUPID")

Regular expressions (regexp)

Regular expressions are concise language for describing patterns in strings. In R, regexp are written as strings, sequences of characters surrounded by quotes "" or ''. Some characters cannot be represented directly in an R string, but must be represented as special characters, having a specific meaning:

  • \\ represents \
  • \" represents "
  • \n represents new line

To see a complete list, you can run ?"'". Also, function writeLines() can be useful to check how R views your string after all special characters have been parsed.

PURRR

CHEATSHEET

purr is a HUGE package enhancing Rs functional programming (FP) toolkit by providing a complete and consistent set of tools for working with functions and vectors. It is very useful when working with lists.

Theres a lot of functionality regarding list management. As the entire content is overwhelming, only most remarkable functionalities will be mentioned.

SOME TRAINING

Prepare a named list containing previous datasets:
- fpkm_sep: Pass Gene_ID to row names; remove Short_name and Locus columns; transpose the data frame; Pass row names to a new first column called Sample.
- microb: Add OTU_ string to start of row names; remove all taxonomy columns; transpose the data frame; Pass row names to a new first column called Sample.
- phenot_sub: Pass row names to a new first column called Sample.
Store the modified datasets in new variables (fpkm_lst, microb_lst).

# FPKM dataset list
fpkm_lst <- select(fpkm_sep, -c(Short_name, Locus)) %>% column_to_rownames("Gene_ID") %>% 
  t() %>% as.data.frame() %>% rownames_to_column("Sample")
# Microb dataset list
microb_lst <- microb
rownames(microb_lst) <- str_glue_data(microb_lst, "OTU_{row.names(microb)}")
microb_lst <- select_if(microb_lst, is.numeric) %>% 
  t() %>% as.data.frame() %>% rownames_to_column("Sample")
# Phenot dataset list
phenot_lst <- rownames_to_column(phenot_sub, "Sample")
# Full list
datalist <- list("RNASEQ" = fpkm_lst, "16S"= microb_lst, "METAD" = phenot_lst)

FORCATS

OVERVIEW

R uses factors to handle categorical variables, variables that have a fixed and known set of possible values. Factors are also helpful for reordering character vectors to improve display. The goal of the forcats package is to provide a suite of tools that solve common problems with factors, including changing the order of levels or the values.

  • fct_reorder(): Reordering a factor by another variable.
  • fct_infreq(): Reordering a factor by the frequency of values.
  • fct_relevel(): Changing the order of a factor by hand.
  • fct_lump(): Collapsing the least/most frequent values of a factor into other.
